        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#oliverioDAI2"/>, p. 267, n. <citedRange>544</citedRange>, fig. 108</bibl>, whence 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>9.316</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>030400</citedRange></bibl>. 
                    Cf. <bibl><ptr target="#lazzarini1976"/>, p. 275, n. <citedRange>700</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#maffre2007"/>, p. 169, n. <citedRange>14</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><w lemma="δεκάτα">Δεκάτα</w>.
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
 </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
            <p>Dîme.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
            <p>Tithe.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
            <p>Decima.</p>
            </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>No god's name was ever written, but it is obvious that the tithe was offered to Apollo, both because he is the only recipient of such offerings at 
                Cyrene and because the fragment was found in his sanctuary.</p>
	<p/>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
